Step-by-step reasoning:

- The index method in App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\MediaController returns a Laravel ResourceCollection of MediaResource items. The data is built from MediaLibrary::first()->media()->paginate($request->input('limit', 20)).
- The MediaResource (App\Http\Resources\Media) defines the shape of each item in the collection: id (integer), name (string), url (string, URL), and thumb_url (string, URL).
- Because the controller uses a ResourceCollection, the JSON response will follow Laravelâ€™s pagination structure: data (array of resource items), links (pagination URLs), and meta (pagination metadata such as current_page, per_page, total, etc.).
- There is no authentication or error handling shown for this endpoint in the provided code, so the successful response is a 200 OK with the described structure.
- The OpenAPI 2.0 (Swagger 2.0) response object for this GET endpoint should describe:
  - 200 response with a schema that is an object containing:
    - data: array of media items with properties id, name, url, thumb_url
    - links: object with first, last, prev, next (strings as URIs; prev/next may be null in pagination)
    - meta: object with pagination metadata (current_page, from, path, per_page, to, total)
- I avoided using $ref and inlined the schema as required.

